\item 2-loop: $-5.0914 \times 10^{-4}$
\item 3-loop: $-8.7892 \times 10^{-5}$
\item 4-loop: $+5.1026 \times 10^{-5}$ \quad (reference value)
\item 5-loop: $+8.3674 \times 10^{-5}$
\end{itemize}
The progression is monotone in sign and the residual changes sign between $3$-loop and $4$-loop. The $4L-3L$ shift ($1.39 \times 10^{-4}$, taken as the difference of residuals) and the $5L-4L$ shift ($3.27 \times 10^{-5}$) are comparable in magnitude to the $4$-loop residual itself. \textbf{We do not claim that the perturbative series has converged at $4$-loop at the level of the residual.} The $4$-loop value is reported as the reference for consistency with standard practice in heavy-quark mass running; it is not a quantity for which a $10^{-5}$-level closure can be interpreted as physically meaningful in the absence of an independent estimate of higher-order coefficients. We discuss this further in Section~\ref{sec:caveats}.

\paragraph{Input correlations are not propagated.} The independent-Gaussian quadrature sum assumes that $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, $m_t(m_t)$, and $\alpha_s(M_Z)$ are uncorrelated. In reality these quantities are extracted with shared lattice systematics, shared $\alpha_s$ assumptions, and shared scheme-conversion uncertainties; the true covariance matrix would couple them. The propagated $\sigma_Q$ reported above is therefore an idealization, and a correlated propagation could shift it modestly in either direction. We have not computed the correlated version because the publicly available correlation matrices are partial; we note the limitation rather than pretending the independent-Gaussian model is exact.


\subsection{Continuous scale dependence}
\label{sec:continuous}

We compute $Q(c, b, t)(\mu)$ as a continuous function of the charm evaluation scale across $\mu \in [1.0, 10000]$~GeV using the precomputed running-mass lookup table (1022 scale points, logarithmically spaced). The full curve is a smooth, monotonic function on each side of a minimum located near $\mu = m_\tau$. The exact zero crossing of $Q(c,b,t)(\mu) - 2/3$ on the interpolation grid occurs at
\begin{equation}
\mu_\star^{\text{crossing}} \;=\; 1.76952~\text{GeV},
\label{eq:crossing}
\end{equation}
which is $7.3$~MeV below $m_\tau = 1.77686$~GeV. Since $dQ/d\mu \approx 6.94 \times 10^{-3}~\text{GeV}^{-1}$ near the crossing, the shift in $Q$ induced by a $\sigma_Q$ shift in inputs corresponds to a $\mu$ shift of approximately $73$~MeV. The observed $7.3$~MeV offset is thus approximately a factor of ten smaller than this propagated width, on the same scale that the residual is a factor of ten smaller than $\sigma_Q$.

The width of the $\mu$-window around $m_\tau$ within which $|Q - 2/3|$ stays below various thresholds is:
\begin{itemize}
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-4}$: $\mu \in [1.76, 1.78]$~GeV, width $\approx 20$~MeV (1.1\% of $m_\tau$)
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 3 \times 10^{-4}$: $\mu \in [1.73, 1.81]$~GeV, width $\approx 80$~MeV (4.5\% of $m_\tau$)
\item $|Q - 2/3| < 5.1 \times 10^{-4} \approx \sigma_Q$: $\mu \in [1.70, 1.84]$~GeV, width $\approx 140$~MeV (7.9\% of $m_\tau$)
\end{itemize}
The $\sigma_Q$-equivalent window is approximately $140$~MeV wide. We note explicitly that the existence of a zero crossing of $Q(c,b,t)(\mu) - 2/3$ somewhere in the perturbative window is not surprising in itself: $Q(c,b,t)(\mu)$ is a smooth continuous function whose range over the perturbative window spans values both above and below $2/3$, so an intermediate-value-theorem crossing is mathematically generic. The descriptive interest, if any, lies in the location of the crossing relative to specific named scales, not in the existence of the crossing itself.


